    <title>Combined summary - OP_CODESEPARATOR Re: BIP Proposal: The Great Consensus Cleanup</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T17:33:52.651494+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2019-March/016740.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin development community has been discussing the vulnerability caused by the use of OP_CODESEPARATOR in transactions and proposing solutions to address it. Some suggestions include increasing transaction weight based on the number of OP_CODESEPARATORS executed and limiting the maximum number of such executions. However, these solutions have their own set of problems and complexities, which have been discussed at length.There are concerns about making changes to the Bitcoin protocol and the potential risks involved. The community is exploring various options to address this vulnerability, including deprecating OP_CODESEPARATOR and increasing transaction weight to make using this opcode more expensive. Some members propose locking in a block height to get rid of it in 10 years and using it as a press opportunity.The importance of balancing security concerns with the principles of open access and backward compatibility that underlie Bitcoin's value proposition is also highlighted. Developers debate the best course of action, taking into account the potential harm to users who have committed funds to non-standard transactions.The bitcoin-dev mailing list has also been discussing the potential risks and benefits of making OP_CODESEPARATOR non-standard. While some argue that making it difficult to use/mine would reduce the risk they create, others question the need for indefinite support of such features. The discussion also considers the likelihood of existing transactions relying on these features versus the harms of continued support, including security risks and friction with other changes.Suggestions for fixing the issue include increasing transaction weight upon execution or limiting the number of OP_CODESEPARATORs allowed per script. However, these come with their own set of problems and complexities. The community is exploring various options to address this vulnerability, including adding restrictions like tx size limits, but there are concerns about rendering some transactions unspendable.Non-standardness is seen as a way to signal potential soft-forks and make them safer for miners to adopt, but it is important to ensure that any changes do not destroy other people's money. The collaborative nature of the Bitcoin development community is highlighted throughout the email thread.The community is also grappling with the trade-offs between non-standardness and user experience, as well as addressing vulnerabilities such as OP_CODESEPARATOR in non-segwit scripts. While there are no easy solutions, the discussions and debates show a commitment to improving the Bitcoin ecosystem.</summary>
